{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3bb1837-95a4-48ee-83be-d08310923201","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob — `**\\*.*` (Line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis is the **biggest offender**. A double-star glob forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree on every evaluation. As the repo grows, this becomes progressively slower. Replace it with targeted globs for specific file types you actually need.\n\n### 2. File I/O during evaluation — `File.ReadAllText` (Line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform **disk I/O execute during evaluation**, not during build. This blocks the evaluator. If you need file content, prefer reading it in a target (deferred to build time) rather than in a `PropertyGroup`.\n\n### 3. Deeply chained imports (3 levels deep)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. Here it's only 3 levels, so the cost is modest, but this pattern becomes expensive if it grows. Flatten the chain where possible—import `level3.props` directly if the intermediate files add little value.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of impact (high → low):**\n\n| Issue | Severity | Fix |\n|---|---|---|\n| `**\\*.*` recursive glob | 🔴 High | Use specific extensions, e.g. `**\\*.txt` |\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | 🟡 Medium | Move to a target with `ReadLinesFromFile` |\n| 3-level import chain | 🟢 Low | Flatten if intermediates are trivial |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6cb4858-0530-4a86-9ac1-0bb90a35810c","outputTokens":464},"id":"f785f220-5e96-4886-8e86-b94960cad7b7","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:05:12.211Z","parentId":"740369a7-3641-49c1-b420-d87ab1aea33d"}
